EXT. DAWES FARM, MAILBOX - DAY

Cricket walks the drive, takes the mail. Bills, a seed catalog — and one heavy envelope, government linen, eagle on the corner.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - DAY

The letter flat on the table. Danny's stopped by on his way somewhere else, reads it over his father's shoulder.

DANNY:
(reading)
"...administrative review has restored annuity status retroactive to separation... enclosed disbursement reflects adjusted back period..."

He slides the check out of the envelope. Looks at the number. Sets it down facing Cricket.

The check: $184,306.00.

DANNY:
And the county sent one too, Dad. Lien's released. Taxes marked satisfied, the whole assessment.

CRICKET:
Fifty years, they never paid a nickel. Zero dollars, zero cents, every quarter on the dot. Now, nine weeks before their launch, somebody in Washington finds my file and gets generous.

Danny looks at the check. At him.

DANNY:
It'd fix the roof. The truck. Probably the next ten years, if you let it sit and don't touch it.

CRICKET:
It would.

He picks up the check, evens its edges against the table, opens the hutch drawer, and lays it inside, flat, under the county's pink seizure copy he never threw away.

He shuts the drawer.

CRICKET:
If they're paying the roster, the roster's real. File says astronaut, active. I'll bill them when I'm back.

Danny looks at him a long moment. Then he takes the empty envelope, folds it once, and drops it in the stove kindling.

DANNY:
I'll get out of your hair. Roads are fine, if you were gonna ask.

CUT TO:
